title: For Sale:  Sig P6 with Sig night sights and 4 magazines
postcontent:
I have a Sig P6 9mm for sale. The P6 was the West German Police sidearm for decades. In America, it was designated as the P225. The West German police used full metal jacket ammunition and had no feeding problems but they did with hollow points. When the P225 was introduced in America, the feed ramp was changed to allow use of hollow point ammo. In the fall of 1987, the P6 barrel was changed so that its feed ramp was identical to the P225. 

 When buying a P6, you should try to get one made after late 1987. This one was made in April of 1991 and has the improved feed ramp.  I have also added Sig night sights to weapon and have changed the grips to Pachmyer rubber grips. The original factory plastic grips are also included. 

 The pistol normally comes with two magazines but I am selling a total of four with the gun.  This is an outstanding shooter. I have often used it as a demonstration gun when teaching new shooters because it made me look so good. It is incredibly accurate and because of the all steel construction, it is absolutely stable during rapid fire. This is the consummate all steel double action/single action concealed carry weapon. It is a single stack 8+1 gun that is absolutely flat and highly concealable. Because it is a Sig, it will last forever. Neither the P225 or the P6 is still manufactured by Sig Sauer. It comes with the original Sig Sauer cardboard box.
Because the night sights cost $100.00 and the two extra magazines were $25.00 each, I am asking $550.00

 ALSO INCLUDED BUT IS A MAGPUL FOREGRIP WITH A LASER SIGHT MOUNTED TO THE SIDE OF THE RAIL, THE BUTTON FOR THE LASER IS ON THE FOREGRIP AND IT MAKES FOR A NICE TACTICAL TOOL OR EASY ACQUISITION ON A TARGET.

The model you have selected is equipped with a special manual decocking lever

To decock the pistol depress the decocking

hammer. Only then will continued depression of the decocking lever safely drop
the hammer to an uncocked position. To return the pistol to firing

upward to its original position. The pistol is then ready to fire by a “double-

rate shooting.
